01:26:50,456 --> 01:26:53,584
<i>I didn't stay home for long,
because I'd made a promise to Bubba,</i>

1148
01:26:53,668 --> 01:26:55,920
<i>and I always try to keep my promise.</i>

1149
01:26:56,003 --> 01:26:57,547
<i>So, I went on down to Bayou La Batre</i>

1150
01:26:57,630 --> 01:27:01,384
<i>to meet Bubba's family
and make their introduction.</i>

1151
01:27:01,467 --> 01:27:05,138
Are you crazy, or just plain stupid?

1152
01:27:05,847 --> 01:27:08,099
Stupid is as stupid does, Mrs Blue.

1153
01:27:08,182 --> 01:27:09,559
I guess.

1154
01:27:10,560 --> 01:27:14,147
<i>And, of course,
I paid my respect to Bubba himself.</i>

1155
01:27:16,149 --> 01:27:18,693
Hey, Bubba, it's me, Forrest Gump.

1156
01:27:21,821 --> 01:27:25,867
I remember everything you said,
and I got it all figured out.

1157
01:27:28,661 --> 01:27:35,460
I'm taking the $24,562
and 47 cents that I got...

1158
01:27:36,544 --> 01:27:40,131
<i>Or, that's left after a new hair cut
and a new suit,</i>

1159
01:27:40,214 --> 01:27:42,175
<i>and I took Mama out
to a real fancy dinner,</i>

1160
01:27:42,258 --> 01:27:45,511
<i>and I bought a bus ticket
and three Dr Peppers.</i>

1161
01:27:46,053 --> 01:27:47,847
Tell me something.

1162
01:27:48,890 --> 01:27:51,017
SHRIMPER: Are you stupid
or something?

1163
01:27:51,100 --> 01:27:53,144
Stupid is as stupid does, sir.

1164
01:27:53,227 --> 01:27:56,189
Well, that's what's left after me saying,

1165
01:27:57,106 --> 01:27:59,233
"When I was in China
on the All-America Ping-Pong team,

1166
01:27:59,358 --> 01:28:03,154
"I just loved playing Ping-Pong with
my Flex-O-Light Ping-Pong paddle,"

1167
01:28:03,237 --> 01:28:04,489
which everybody knows isn't true,

1168
01:28:04,572 --> 01:28:05,948
but Mama says it's just a little white lie

1169
01:28:06,032 --> 01:28:08,201
so it wouldn't hurt nobody.

1170
01:28:09,619 --> 01:28:15,541
So, anyway, I'm putting all that on gas,
ropes and new nets

1171
01:28:16,292 --> 01:28:18,044
and a brand-new shrimping boat.

1172
01:28:39,732 --> 01:28:42,985
<i>Now, Bubba had told me everything
he knew about shrimping,</i>

1173
01:28:43,069 --> 01:28:45,404
<i>but you know what I found out?</i>

1174
01:28:47,073 --> 01:28:49,408
<i>Shrimping is tough.</i>

1175
01:28:51,619 --> 01:28:53,454
I only caught five.

1176
01:28:53,579 --> 01:28:55,414
A couple more,
you could have yourself a cocktail.

1177
01:28:55,498 --> 01:28:56,582
(CHUCKLING)

1178
01:29:00,253 --> 01:29:02,004
Hey, you ever think
about naming this old boat?

1179
01:29:02,088 --> 01:29:04,757
It's bad luck
to have a boat without a name.

1180
01:29:07,134 --> 01:29:11,973
<i>I'd never named a boat before,
but there was only one I could think of,</i>

1181
01:29:13,140 --> 01:29:16,352
<i>the most beautiful name
in the wide world.</i>

1182
01:29:20,690 --> 01:29:23,901
<i>(GET DOWN TONIGHT</i> PLAYING)

1183
01:29:37,373 --> 01:29:40,209
<i>Now, I hadn't heard from Jenny
in a long while,</i>

1184
01:29:40,293 --> 01:29:42,837
<i>but I thought about her a lot,</i>

1185
01:29:42,962 --> 01:29:46,424
<i>and I hoped that whatever
she was doing made her happy.</i>

1186
01:31:32,697 --> 01:31:35,241
<i>I thought about Jenny all the time.</i>

1187
01:31:54,760 --> 01:31:55,761
(LAUGHS)

1188
01:31:59,890 --> 01:32:01,058
Hey!

1189
01:32:24,915 --> 01:32:29,587
Lieutenant Dan,
what are you doing here?

1190
01:32:29,670 --> 01:32:33,591
Well, thought I'd try out my sea legs.

1191
01:32:33,674 --> 01:32:37,428
But you ain't got no legs,
Lieutenant Dan.

1192
01:32:37,511 --> 01:32:39,805
Yes, I know that.

1193
01:32:40,139 --> 01:32:42,183
You wrote me a letter, you idiot.

1194
01:32:42,308 --> 01:32:46,854
Well, well. Captain Forrest Gump.
I had to see this for myself.

1195
01:32:48,481 --> 01:32:55,362
And I told you if you were ever
a shrimp boat captain

1196
01:32:55,488 --> 01:32:58,074
that I'd be your first mate.
Well, here I am.

1197
01:32:58,157 --> 01:33:01,285
- I am a man of my word.
- Okay.

1198
01:33:01,368 --> 01:33:05,372
Yeah, but don't you be thinking that
I'm going to be calling you "sir."

1199
01:33:05,498 --> 01:33:06,832
No, sir.

1200
01:33:15,716 --> 01:33:18,010
That's my boat.

1201
01:33:20,596 --> 01:33:26,060
DAN: I have a feeling if we head
due east, we'll find some shrimp,

1202
01:33:26,185 --> 01:33:27,770
so take a left.

1203
01:33:29,188 --> 01:33:32,108
- Take a left!
- Which way?

1204
01:33:32,191 --> 01:33:34,860
Over there! They're over there!

1205
01:33:35,528 --> 01:33:39,365
- Get on the wheel and take a left!
- Okay.

1206
01:33:40,574 --> 01:33:44,703
Gump, what are you doing?
Take a left! Left!

1207
01:33:47,081 --> 01:33:50,709
That's where we're going
to find those shrimp, my boy!

1208
01:33:52,294 --> 01:33:53,879
That's where we'll find them.

1209
01:34:06,559 --> 01:34:10,688
- Still no shrimp, Lieutenant Dan.
- Okay, so I was wrong.

1210
01:34:11,397 --> 01:34:14,608
How are we going to find them?

1211
01:34:14,733 --> 01:34:17,236
Well, maybe you should
just pray for shrimp.

1212
01:34:17,945 --> 01:34:20,948
(SINGING GOSPEL MUSIC)

1213
01:34:23,868 --> 01:34:26,537
<i>FORREST:
So, I went to church every Sunday.</i>

1214
01:34:27,788 --> 01:34:29,790
<i>Sometimes Lieutenant Dan came, too,</i>

1215
01:34:29,915 --> 01:34:32,918
<i>though I think
he left the praying up to me.</i>

1216
01:34:48,392 --> 01:34:52,771
- No shrimp.
- Where the hell's this God of yours?

1217
01:34:53,606 --> 01:34:59,320
<i>It's funny Lieutenant Dan said that,
'cause right then, God showed up.</i>

1218
01:35:16,170 --> 01:35:21,008
- DAN: You'll never sink this boat!
<i>- Now, me, I was scared,</i>

1219
01:35:21,133 --> 01:35:24,178
<i>but Lieutenant Dan, he was mad.</i>

1220
01:35:24,303 --> 01:35:25,638
Come on!

1221
01:35:28,766 --> 01:35:33,979
You call this a storm?
Come on, you son of a bitch!

1222
01:35:36,106 --> 01:35:40,486
It's time for a showdown! You and me!

1223
01:35:40,611 --> 01:35:44,490
I'm right here! Come and get me!

1224
01:35:44,573 --> 01:35:46,158
(CACKLING)

1225
01:35:46,283 --> 01:35:50,162
You'll never sink this boat!

1226
01:35:52,206 --> 01:35:54,375
<i>Hurricane Carmen
came through here yesterday,</i>

1227
01:35:54,500 --> 01:35:57,044
<i>destroying nearly everything in its path.</i>

1228
01:35:57,169 --> 01:35:59,672
<i>And as in other towns
up and down the coast,</i>

1229
01:35:59,838 --> 01:36:02,216
<i>Bayou La Batre's
entire shrimping industry</i>

1230
01:36:02,299 --> 01:36:06,178
<i>has fallen victim to Carmen
and has been left in utter ruin.</i>

1231
01:36:06,303 --> 01:36:09,431
<i>Speaking with local officials,
this reporter has learned,</i>

1232
01:36:09,515 --> 01:36:12,977
<i>in fact, only one shrimping boat
actually survived the storm.</i>

1233
01:36:13,352 --> 01:36:15,980
Louise. Louise, there's Forrest.

1234
01:36:16,689 --> 01:36:18,691
<i>FORREST: After that,
shrimping was easy.</i>

1235
01:36:24,363 --> 01:36:27,491
<i>Since people still needed
them shrimps for shrimp cocktails</i>

1236
01:36:27,574 --> 01:36:31,704
and barbecues and all,
and we were the only boat left standing,

1237
01:36:31,870 --> 01:36:35,124
Bubba-Gump Shrimp's what they got.

1238
01:36:35,207 --> 01:36:39,795
We got a whole bunch of boats,
12 <i>Jennys,</i>

1239
01:36:39,878 --> 01:36:43,382
a big old warehouse. We even have
hats that say "Bubba-Gump" on them.

1240
01:36:43,716 --> 01:36:47,011
Bubba-Gump Shrimp.
It's a household name.

1241
01:36:47,219 --> 01:36:48,929
Hold on there, boy.

1242
01:36:49,054 --> 01:36:53,600
Are you telling me you're the owner of
the Bubba-Gump Shrimp Corporation?

1243
01:36:53,726 --> 01:36:56,729
Yes, sir. We got more money
than Davy Crockett.

1244
01:36:56,812 --> 01:36:58,272
(LAUGHING)

1245
01:36:58,355 --> 01:37:02,401
Boy, I heard some whoppers in my time,
but that tops them all.

1246
01:37:05,112 --> 01:37:07,906
We was sitting next to a millionaire.

1247
01:37:11,410 --> 01:37:16,040
Well, I thought it was a very lovely story,

1248
01:37:16,457 --> 01:37:21,086
and you tell it so well,
with such enthusiasm.

1249
01:37:22,796 --> 01:37:25,466
Would you like to see
what Lieutenant Dan looks like?

1250
01:37:25,591 --> 01:37:27,092
Well, yes, I would.

1251
01:37:32,097 --> 01:37:34,141
That's him right there.

1252
01:37:36,477 --> 01:37:38,729
And let me tell you something
about Lieutenant Dan...

1253
01:37:39,897 --> 01:37:40,939
Forrest,

1254
01:37:46,487 --> 01:37:49,281
I never thanked you for saving my life.

1255
01:38:15,307 --> 01:38:21,605
<i>FORREST: He never actually said so,
but I think he made his peace with God.</i>

1256
01:38:27,486 --> 01:38:28,987
<i>(GUNSHOTS FIRING)</i>

1257
01:38:29,279 --> 01:38:31,490
<i>For the second time in 17 days,</i>

1258
01:38:31,615 --> 01:38:35,077
<i>President Ford escaped
possible assassination today.</i>

1259
01:38:35,160 --> 01:38:36,453
<i>MARGO: Base to</i> Jenny 1.

1260
01:38:36,537 --> 01:38:40,040
<i>- Base to</i> Jenny 1.
<i>- Jenny 1</i>. Go, Margo.

1261
01:38:40,124 --> 01:38:41,625
<i>Forrest has a phone call.</i>

1262
01:38:41,708 --> 01:38:44,211
Yeah, well, you'll have to tell them
to call him back.

1263
01:38:44,294 --> 01:38:47,673
- He is indisposed at the moment.
<i>- His mama's sick.</i>

1264
01:39:08,360 --> 01:39:10,737
- Where's Mama?
- She's upstairs.

1265
01:39:13,574 --> 01:39:15,534
Hi, Forrest.

1266
01:39:16,493 --> 01:39:19,037
- DOCTOR: I'll see you tomorrow.
- All right.

1267
01:39:25,711 --> 01:39:28,881
We sure got you straightened out,
didn't we, boy?

1268
01:39:40,225 --> 01:39:44,188
- What's the matter, Mama?
- I'm dying, Forrest.

1269
01:39:47,524 --> 01:39:49,902
Come on in, sit down over here.

1270
01:40:04,249 --> 01:40:07,753
- Why are you dying, Mama?
- It's my time.

1271
01:40:08,754 --> 01:40:10,631
It's just my time.

1272
01:40:12,090 --> 01:40:16,261
Now, don't you be afraid, sweetheart.

1273
01:40:17,888 --> 01:40:20,265
Death is just a part of life,

1274
01:40:21,266 --> 01:40:23,894
something we're all destined to do.

1275
01:40:25,729 --> 01:40:30,108
I didn't know it,
but I was destined to be your mama.

1276
01:40:30,943 --> 01:40:34,530
- I did the best I could.
- You did good, Mama.

1277
01:40:35,322 --> 01:40:40,494
Well, I happen to believe
you make your own destiny.

1278
01:40:41,995 --> 01:40:45,249
You have to do the best
with what God gave you.

1279
01:40:49,127 --> 01:40:51,255
What's my destiny, Mama?

1280
01:40:53,423 --> 01:40:56,635
You're going to have
to figure that out for yourself.

1281
01:40:57,928 --> 01:41:00,889
Life is a box of chocolates, Forrest.

1282
01:41:00,973 --> 01:41:03,141
You never know
what you're going to get.

1283
01:41:03,267 --> 01:41:07,646
<i>Mama always had a way of explaining
things so I could understand them.</i>

1284
01:41:07,729 --> 01:41:09,940
I will miss you, Forrest.

1285
01:41:11,775 --> 01:41:15,821
<i>She had got the cancer
and died on a Tuesday.</i>

1286
01:41:17,322 --> 01:41:20,659
<i>I bought her a new hat
with little flowers on it.</i>

1287
01:41:23,704 --> 01:41:26,999
And that's all I have to say about that.

1288
01:41:33,839 --> 01:41:36,133
Didn't you say you were waiting
for the number seven bus?

1289
01:41:36,216 --> 01:41:39,011
There'll be another one along shortly.

1290
01:41:42,848 --> 01:41:46,435
Now, because I had been a football star,
and a war hero,

1291
01:41:46,518 --> 01:41:49,646
and a national celebrity,
and a shrimping boat captain,

1292
01:41:50,147 --> 01:41:53,358
and a college graduate,
the city fathers of Greenbow, Alabama

1293
01:41:53,483 --> 01:41:56,695
decided to get together
and offered me a fine job.

1294
01:41:58,071 --> 01:42:01,742
<i>So, I never went back to work
for Lieutenant Dan,</i>

1295
01:42:01,867 --> 01:42:04,578
<i>though he did take care
of my Bubba-Gump money.</i>

1296
01:42:04,703 --> 01:42:09,291
<i>He got me invested
in some kind of fruit company.</i>

1297
01:42:09,374 --> 01:42:10,959
<i>And so then, I got a call from him saying</i>

1298
01:42:11,043 --> 01:42:14,504
we don't have to worry about money
no more, and I said,

1299
01:42:14,588 --> 01:42:16,882
"That's good. One less thing."

1300
01:42:17,382 --> 01:42:19,509
(SINGING GOSPEL MUSIC)

1301
01:42:19,926 --> 01:42:23,847
<i>Now, Mama said there's only
so much fortune a man really needs,</i>

1302
01:42:24,598 --> 01:42:27,434
<i>and the rest is just for showing off.</i>

1303
01:42:27,517 --> 01:42:31,396
<i>So, I gave a whole bunch of it
to the Foursquare gospel church,</i>

1304
01:42:33,857 --> 01:42:38,028
<i>and I gave a whole bunch to the
Bayou La Batre fishing hospital.</i>

1305
01:42:40,906 --> 01:42:45,452
<i>And even though Bubba was dead
and Lieutenant Dan said I was nuts,</i>

1306
01:42:45,577 --> 01:42:48,205
<i>I gave Bubba's mama Bubba's share.</i>

1307
01:42:52,417 --> 01:42:54,127
You know what?

1308
01:42:55,379 --> 01:42:58,382
<i>She didn't have to work
in nobody's kitchen no more.</i>

1309
01:42:58,465 --> 01:43:00,092
That smells wonderful.

1310
01:43:00,926 --> 01:43:04,846
<i>And 'cause I was a gazillionaire
and I liked doing it so much,</i>

1311
01:43:04,930 --> 01:43:07,265
<i>I cut that grass for free.</i>

1312
01:43:11,061 --> 01:43:13,939
<i>But at night time
when there was nothing to do</i>

1313
01:43:14,022 --> 01:43:16,400
<i>and the house was all empty,</i>

1314
01:43:17,401 --> 01:43:19,778
<i>I'd always think of Jenny.</i>

1315
01:44:23,467 --> 01:44:26,636
<i>And then, she was there.</i>

1316
01:44:59,628 --> 01:45:02,798
- Hello, Forrest.
- Hello, Jenny.

1317
01:45:14,351 --> 01:45:16,978
<i>Jenny came back and stayed with me.</i>

1318
01:45:18,563 --> 01:45:22,234
<i>Maybe it was because
she had nowhere else to go,</i>

1319
01:45:22,359 --> 01:45:26,071
<i>or maybe it was because she was
so tired, 'cause she went to bed</i>

1320
01:45:26,196 --> 01:45:30,158
<i>and slept and slept,
like she hadn't slept in years.</i>

1321
01:45:31,409 --> 01:45:33,703
<i>It was wonderful having her home.</i>

1322
01:45:35,038 --> 01:45:40,168
<i>Every day we'd take a walk and
I'd jabber on like a monkey in a tree,</i>

1323
01:45:40,252 --> 01:45:42,796
<i>and she'd listen about Ping-Ponging,
and shrimping,</i>

1324
01:45:42,879 --> 01:45:47,175
<i>and Mama making a trip up to heaven.
I did all the talking.</i>

1325
01:45:47,259 --> 01:45:50,595
<i>Jenny most of the time was real quiet.</i>

1326
01:46:30,760 --> 01:46:33,972
How could you do this?

1327
01:46:47,277 --> 01:46:49,279
(CRYING)

1328
01:47:10,926 --> 01:47:14,262
<i>Sometimes I guess there
just aren't enough rocks.</i>

1329
01:47:16,473 --> 01:47:20,977
<i>I never really knew why she came back,
but I didn't care.</i>

1330
01:47:21,144 --> 01:47:25,440
<i>It was like olden times.
We was like peas and carrots again.</i>

1331
01:47:27,525 --> 01:47:31,863
<i>Every day, I'd pick pretty flowers
and put them in her room for her,</i>

1332
01:47:33,365 --> 01:47:36,952
<i>and she gave me the best gift anyone
could ever get in the wide world.</i>

1333
01:47:37,035 --> 01:47:39,871
- New shoes.
- They make them just for running.

1334
01:47:44,876 --> 01:47:48,171
<i>And she even showed me how to dance.</i>

1335
01:47:56,346 --> 01:48:00,558
<i>And, well, we was like family,
Jenny and me.</i>

1336
01:48:04,312 --> 01:48:07,232
<i>And it was the happiest time in my life.</i>

1337
01:48:26,876 --> 01:48:28,670
<i>MAN ON TV:...and this Fourth is
witnessing one of the</i>

1338
01:48:28,753 --> 01:48:31,756
<i>largest fireworks displays
in the nation's...</i>

1339
01:48:31,840 --> 01:48:34,759
- You done watching it?
<i>- ...here in New York Harbour...</i>

1340
01:48:34,884 --> 01:48:36,678
- I'm going to bed.
<i>- ...with a spectacular display</i>

1341
01:48:36,761 --> 01:48:39,806
<i>of tall ships earlier.
The Statue of Liberty...</i>

1342
01:48:46,855 --> 01:48:48,857
Will you marry me?

1343
01:48:53,778 --> 01:48:56,740
I'd make a good husband, Jenny.

1344
01:48:59,409 --> 01:49:01,453
You would, Forrest.

1345
01:49:03,288 --> 01:49:05,623
But you won't marry me.

1346
01:49:07,917 --> 01:49:10,128
You don't want to marry me.

1347
01:49:13,715 --> 01:49:16,134
Why don't you love me, Jenny?

1348
01:49:21,139 --> 01:49:23,266
I'm not a smart man,

1349
01:49:24,976 --> 01:49:27,395
but I know what love is.

1350
01:50:04,432 --> 01:50:05,683
Jenny.

1351
01:50:07,602 --> 01:50:10,105
Forrest, I do love you.

1352
01:51:03,241 --> 01:51:06,911
- Where are you running off to?
- I'm not running.

1353
01:52:38,503 --> 01:52:43,841
<i>That day, for no particular reason,
I decided to go for a little run.</i>

1354
01:52:45,009 --> 01:52:49,430
<i>So, I ran to the end of the road,
and when I got there,</i>

1355
01:52:49,514 --> 01:52:51,266
<i>I thought maybe I'd run
to the end of town.</i>

1356
01:52:51,349 --> 01:52:52,517
<i>REPORTER: President Carter, suffering</i>

1357
01:52:52,600 --> 01:52:54,602
<i>from heat exhaustion,
fell into the arms of...</i>

1358
01:52:54,686 --> 01:52:56,354
<i>FORREST: And when I got there,</i>

1359
01:52:56,437 --> 01:53:00,608
<i>I thought maybe I'd just
run across Greenbow County.</i>

1360
01:53:00,692 --> 01:53:03,111
<i>And I figured since I'd run this far,</i>

1361
01:53:03,194 --> 01:53:06,447
<i>maybe I'd just run across
the great state of Alabama.</i>

1362
01:53:06,531 --> 01:53:07,740
<i>And that's what I did.</i>

1363
01:53:08,366 --> 01:53:10,952
I ran clear across Alabama.

1364
01:53:11,202 --> 01:53:14,372
For no particular reason,
I just kept on going.

1365
01:53:15,707 --> 01:53:17,292
I ran clear to the ocean.

1366
01:53:23,172 --> 01:53:26,342
<i>And when I got there,
I figured since I'd gone this far,</i>

1367
01:53:26,884 --> 01:53:29,721
<i>might as well turn around
and just keep on going.</i>

1368
01:53:33,474 --> 01:53:38,062
<i>And when I got to another ocean,
I figured since I'd gone this far,</i>

1369
01:53:39,856 --> 01:53:43,568
<i>I might as well just turn back
and keep right on going.</i>

1370
01:53:44,736 --> 01:53:49,574
<i>When I got tired, I slept.
When I got hungry, I ate.</i>

1371
01:53:49,657 --> 01:53:52,702
When I had to go, you know...

1372
01:53:54,329 --> 01:53:55,496
I went.

1373
01:53:55,580 --> 01:53:58,583
And so, you just ran.

1374
01:54:00,335 --> 01:54:01,419
Yeah.

1375
01:54:01,502 --> 01:54:04,255
<i>(RUNNING ON EMPTY</i> PLAYING)

1376
01:54:36,704 --> 01:54:41,959
<i>FORREST: I'd think a lot about Mama
and Bubba and Lieutenant Dan.</i>

1377
01:54:42,960 --> 01:54:46,464
<i>But most of all, I thought about Jenny.</i>

1378
01:54:47,548 --> 01:54:49,717
<i>I thought about her a lot.</i>

1379
01:54:50,468 --> 01:54:53,554
<i>For more than two years now,
a man named Forrest Gump,</i>

1380
01:54:53,638 --> 01:54:57,058
<i>a gardener from Greenbow, Alabama,
stopping only to sleep,</i>

1381
01:54:57,141 --> 01:54:59,310
<i>has been running across America.</i>

1382
01:54:59,394 --> 01:55:01,396
<i>Charles Cooper brings us this report.</i>

1383
01:55:02,313 --> 01:55:04,732
<i>For the fourth time
on his journey across America,</i>

1384
01:55:04,816 --> 01:55:07,652
<i>Forrest Gump,
the gardener from Greenbow, Alabama,</i>

1385
01:55:07,777 --> 01:55:10,655
<i>is about to cross
the Mississippi River again today.</i>

1386
01:55:11,280 --> 01:55:13,324
- I'll be damned. Forrest?
<i>- Sir, why are you running?</i>

1387
01:55:13,408 --> 01:55:14,492
Why are you running?

1388
01:55:14,575 --> 01:55:16,160
Are you doing this for world peace?

1389
01:55:16,244 --> 01:55:17,578
Are you doing this for the homeless?

1390
01:55:17,662 --> 01:55:20,665
- Are you running for women's rights?
- Or for the environment?

1391
01:55:20,748 --> 01:55:21,749
Or for animals?

1392
01:55:21,833 --> 01:55:24,752
<i>FORREST: They just couldn't believe
that somebody would do all that running</i>

1393
01:55:24,836 --> 01:55:26,212
<i>for no particular reason.</i>

1394
01:55:26,295 --> 01:55:28,256
REPORTER: Why are you doing this?

1395
01:55:28,339 --> 01:55:30,842
I just felt like running.

1396
01:55:30,967 --> 01:55:33,344
I just felt like running.

1397
01:55:33,469 --> 01:55:36,681
It's you. I can't believe it's really you.

1398
01:55:37,515 --> 01:55:42,645
Now, for some reason, what I was doing
seemed to make sense to people.

1399
01:55:42,812 --> 01:55:44,939
I mean, it was like an alarm
went off in my head, you know?

1400
01:55:45,022 --> 01:55:46,858
I said,
"Here's a guy that's got his act together.

1401
01:55:46,983 --> 01:55:48,943
"Here's somebody
who's got it all figured out.

1402
01:55:49,026 --> 01:55:53,114
"Here's somebody who has the answer."
I'll follow you anywhere, Mr Gump.

1403
01:55:53,197 --> 01:55:55,032
<i>So, I got company.</i>

1404
01:55:56,868 --> 01:56:02,707
<i>And after that, I got more company.
And then, even more people joined in.</i>

1405
01:56:05,168 --> 01:56:08,379
Somebody later told me
it gave people hope.

1406
01:56:10,173 --> 01:56:13,551
Now... Now, I don't know
anything about that,

1407
01:56:14,385 --> 01:56:16,971
<i>but some of those people
asked me if I could help them out.</i>

1408
01:56:17,180 --> 01:56:20,433
Hey, man, hey, listen, I was wondering
if you might help me, huh?

1409
01:56:20,516 --> 01:56:22,268
Listen, I'm in the
bumper sticker business

1410
01:56:22,351 --> 01:56:24,103
and I've been trying
to think up a good slogan.

1411
01:56:24,187 --> 01:56:27,315
And since you have been such a big
inspiration to the people around here,

1412
01:56:27,398 --> 01:56:29,317
I thought you might
be able to help me jump into...

1413
01:56:29,400 --> 01:56:33,029
Whoa, man! You just ran through
a big pile of dog shit!

1414
01:56:34,572 --> 01:56:37,241
- It happens.
- What, shit?

1415
01:56:38,743 --> 01:56:40,703
Sometimes.

1416
01:56:42,580 --> 01:56:45,249
<i>And some years later,
I heard that that fellow</i>

1417
01:56:45,333 --> 01:56:47,168
<i>did come up with
a bumper sticker slogan,</i>

1418
01:56:47,251 --> 01:56:50,254
<i>and he made a lot of money off of it.</i>

1419
01:56:51,714 --> 01:56:53,925
<i>Another time, I was running along,</i>

1420
01:56:54,050 --> 01:56:57,345
<i>somebody who had lost all his money
in the T-shirt business,</i>

1421
01:56:57,428 --> 01:56:59,472
<i>he wanted to put my face on a T-shirt,</i>

1422
01:56:59,555 --> 01:57:02,517
<i>but he couldn't draw that well,
and he didn't have a camera.</i>

1423
01:57:02,600 --> 01:57:06,103
Here, use this one.
Nobody likes that colour anyway.

1424
01:57:10,942 --> 01:57:12,610
FORREST: Have a nice day.

1425
01:57:14,237 --> 01:57:15,363
<i>Well, some years later,</i>

1426
01:57:15,446 --> 01:57:19,367
<i>I found out that that man
did come up with an idea for a T-shirt.</i>

1427
01:57:19,450 --> 01:57:21,827
<i>He made a lot of money off of it.</i>

1428
01:57:24,622 --> 01:57:29,043
<i>Anyway, like I was saying,
I had a lot of company.</i>

1429
01:57:30,294 --> 01:57:31,462
<i>My mama always said,</i>

1430
01:57:31,546 --> 01:57:35,967
<i>"You got to put the past behind you
before you can move on."</i>

1431
01:57:37,635 --> 01:57:40,972
<i>And I think that's what
my running was all about.</i>

1432
01:57:41,806 --> 01:57:45,810
<i>I had run for three years, two months,</i>

1433
01:57:46,060 --> 01:57:48,396
<i>14 days and 16 hours.</i>

1434
01:58:04,078 --> 01:58:06,414
Quiet. Quiet.
He's going to say something.

1435
01:58:17,842 --> 01:58:19,594
I'm pretty tired.

1436
01:58:22,430 --> 01:58:24,473
Think I'll go home now.

1437
01:58:43,034 --> 01:58:45,494
Now what are we supposed to do?

1438
01:58:46,454 --> 01:58:50,708
<i>And just like that,
my running days was over.</i>

1439
01:58:52,668 --> 01:58:54,420
<i>So, I went home to Alabama.</i>

1440
01:58:55,212 --> 01:58:59,091
<i>REPORTER: Moments ago, at 2:25 p.m.,
as President Reagan was leaving the...</i>

1441
01:58:59,175 --> 01:59:00,843
<i>(GUNSHOTS FIRING)</i>

1442
01:59:01,135 --> 01:59:05,306
<i>... five or six gunshots were fired
by an unknown would-be assassin.</i>

1443
01:59:05,806 --> 01:59:08,142
<i>The President was shot in the chest,
and the assailant...</i>

1444
01:59:08,225 --> 01:59:10,186
I picked up the mail.

1445
01:59:10,978 --> 01:59:14,815
And one day, out of the blue clear sky,
I got a letter from Jenny,

1446
01:59:14,899 --> 01:59:19,153
wondering if I could come down
to Savannah and see her,

1447
01:59:19,236 --> 01:59:21,822
and that's what I'm doing here.

1448
01:59:21,906 --> 01:59:24,492
She saw me on TV, running.

1449
01:59:24,575 --> 01:59:28,829
I'm supposed to go on the
number nine bus to Richmond Street

1450
01:59:28,913 --> 01:59:35,836
and get off and go one block left
to 1947 Henry Street, Apartment 4.

1451
01:59:35,920 --> 01:59:39,590
Why, you don't need to take a bus.

1452
01:59:39,715 --> 01:59:44,261
Henry Street is just five
or six blocks down that way.

1453
01:59:46,097 --> 01:59:48,432
- Down that way?
- Down that way.

1454
01:59:51,435 --> 01:59:53,354
It was nice talking to you.

1455
01:59:53,604 --> 01:59:54,563
(CAR HORN HONKING)

1456
01:59:54,647 --> 01:59:57,274
I hope everything works out for you!

1457
02:00:04,782 --> 02:00:06,450
Hey!

1458
02:00:06,867 --> 02:00:08,536
Forrest!

1459
02:00:08,786 --> 02:00:12,039
How you doing? Come in, come in!

1460
02:00:12,123 --> 02:00:13,332
I got your letter.

1461
02:00:13,416 --> 02:00:16,043
I was wondering about that.

1462
02:00:17,586 --> 02:00:19,380
Is this your house?

1463
02:00:19,463 --> 02:00:22,550
Yeah. It's messy right now.
I just got off work.

1464
02:00:22,633 --> 02:00:26,345
It's nice. You got air conditioning.

1465
02:00:33,227 --> 02:00:35,271
- Thank you.
- I ate some.

1466
02:00:38,065 --> 02:00:43,487
Hey, I kept a scrapbook
of your clippings and everything.

1467
02:00:43,612 --> 02:00:45,239
There you are.

1468
02:00:46,824 --> 02:00:48,200
And this, I got you running.

1469
02:00:51,162 --> 02:00:53,330
I ran a long way,

1470
02:00:53,831 --> 02:00:55,666
for a long time.

1471
02:00:57,877 --> 02:00:59,378
And there...

1472
02:01:05,885 --> 02:01:09,346
Listen, Forrest,
I don't know how to say this.

1473
02:01:11,849 --> 02:01:16,187
I just I want to apologise
for anything that I ever did to you,

1474
02:01:16,312 --> 02:01:21,567
'cause I was messed up
for a long time, and...

1475
02:01:21,901 --> 02:01:22,902
(KNOCKING AT DOOR)

1476
02:01:23,235 --> 02:01:24,236
Yoo-hoo!

1477
02:01:24,361 --> 02:01:25,988
- Hey.
- Hi.

1478
02:01:26,197 --> 02:01:27,198
Hey, you.

1479
02:01:28,365 --> 02:01:31,327
- This is an old friend from Alabama.
- How do you do?

1480
02:01:31,410 --> 02:01:34,497
JENNY: Listen, next week my schedule
changes, so I'll be able to... But thanks...

1481
02:01:34,580 --> 02:01:36,624
No problem. Got to go, Jen,
I'm double-parked.

1482
02:01:36,707 --> 02:01:38,584
- Okay. Thanks.
- Bye.

1483
02:01:42,046 --> 02:01:44,799
This is my very good friend, Mr Gump.
Can you say hi to him?

1484
02:01:44,882 --> 02:01:47,968
- Hello, Mr Gump.
- Hello.

1485
02:01:48,052 --> 02:01:51,055
- Can I go watch TV now?
- Yes, you can. Just keep it low.

1486
02:01:53,891 --> 02:01:57,228
- You're a mama, Jenny.
- I'm a mama.

1487
02:02:00,105 --> 02:02:01,941
His name's Forrest.

1488
02:02:03,067 --> 02:02:04,401
Like me.

1489
02:02:06,028 --> 02:02:08,155
I named him after his daddy.

1490
02:02:09,114 --> 02:02:11,575
He got a daddy named Forrest, too?

1491
02:02:12,868 --> 02:02:14,912
You're his daddy, Forrest.

1492
02:02:29,385 --> 02:02:30,594
Hey.

1493
02:02:31,762 --> 02:02:34,640
Forrest, look at me. Look at me, Forrest.

1494
02:02:37,226 --> 02:02:41,355
There's nothing you need to do, okay?
You didn't do anything wrong.

1495
02:02:41,897 --> 02:02:43,274
Okay?

1496
02:02:47,611 --> 02:02:49,488
Isn't he beautiful?

1497
02:02:50,489 --> 02:02:53,450
He's the most beautiful thing
I've ever seen.

1498
02:02:57,246 --> 02:02:58,330
But...

1499
02:03:02,001 --> 02:03:04,879
Is he smart, or...

1500
02:03:04,962 --> 02:03:08,966
He's very smart.
He's one of the smartest in his class.

1501
02:03:18,309 --> 02:03:20,769
Yeah, it's okay. Go talk to him.

1502
02:03:30,112 --> 02:03:32,948
- What are you watching?
- Bert and Ernie.

1503
02:03:56,055 --> 02:03:57,848
Forrest,

1504
02:03:59,308 --> 02:04:00,851
I'm sick.

1505
02:04:03,520 --> 02:04:07,149
What, do you have
a cough due to a cold?

1506
02:04:07,232 --> 02:04:09,610
I have some kind of virus,

1507
02:04:09,693 --> 02:04:12,404
and the doctors don't...
They don't know what it is,

1508
02:04:12,529 --> 02:04:15,532
and there isn't anything
they can do about it.

1509
02:04:19,912 --> 02:04:22,206
You could come home with me.

1510
02:04:23,874 --> 02:04:29,546
Jenny, you and little Forrest could
come stay at my house in Greenbow.

1511
02:04:33,884 --> 02:04:36,679
I'll take care of you if you're sick.

1512
02:04:39,056 --> 02:04:41,350
Would you marry me, Forrest?

1513
02:04:46,605 --> 02:04:47,856
Okay.

1514
02:04:48,899 --> 02:04:50,567
MINISTER: Please take your seats.

1515
02:04:54,405 --> 02:04:56,740
Forrest? It's time to start.

1516
02:05:16,135 --> 02:05:17,720
Hi.

1517
02:05:18,595 --> 02:05:20,097
Your tie.

1518
02:05:32,651 --> 02:05:34,278
Lieutenant Dan.

1519
02:05:49,626 --> 02:05:51,587
Lieutenant Dan.

1520
02:05:52,421 --> 02:05:54,089
Hello, Forrest.

1521
02:05:54,757 --> 02:05:57,426
You got new legs. New legs!

1522
02:05:58,635 --> 02:06:02,431
Yeah. I got new legs. Custom-made.

1523
02:06:03,140 --> 02:06:07,144
Titanium alloy.
It's what they use on the space shuttle.

1524
02:06:10,981 --> 02:06:12,483
Magic legs.

1525
02:06:14,485 --> 02:06:18,864
This is my fiancée, Susan.

1526
02:06:21,658 --> 02:06:25,037
- Lieutenant Dan.
- Hi, Forrest.

1527
02:06:27,122 --> 02:06:30,334
Lieutenant Dan, this is my Jenny.

1528
02:06:30,709 --> 02:06:33,712
Hey. It's nice to meet you finally.

1529
02:06:43,847 --> 02:06:48,018
MINISTER: Do you, Forrest,
take Jenny to be your wife?

1530
02:06:49,895 --> 02:06:54,149
Do you, Jenny,
take Forrest to be your husband?

1531
02:06:55,484 --> 02:06:58,862
And so I pronounce you man and wife.

1532
02:07:29,726 --> 02:07:31,603
- Hey.
- Hey.

1533
02:07:45,284 --> 02:07:47,077
Hey, Forrest.

1534
02:07:52,416 --> 02:07:54,209
Were you scared in Vietnam?

1535
02:07:55,878 --> 02:07:58,213
Yes. Well, I...

1536
02:07:59,548 --> 02:08:01,258
I don't know.

1537
02:08:01,967 --> 02:08:06,930
<i>Sometimes it would stop raining long
enough for the stars to come out.</i>

1538
02:08:10,058 --> 02:08:12,102
<i>And then it was nice.</i>

1539
02:08:15,480 --> 02:08:19,443
It was like just before the sun
goes to bed down on the bayou.

1540
02:08:20,736 --> 02:08:24,615
<i>There was always
a million sparkles on the water.</i>

1541
02:08:26,408 --> 02:08:30,329
<i>Like that mountain lake.
It was so clear, Jenny,</i>

1542
02:08:30,454 --> 02:08:35,042
<i>it looked like there were two skies,
one on top of the other.</i>

1543
02:08:37,586 --> 02:08:40,631
And then, in the desert,
when the sun comes up,

1544
02:08:43,091 --> 02:08:47,262
<i>I couldn't tell where heaven stopped</i>

1545
02:08:47,804 --> 02:08:50,182
<i>and the earth began.</i>

1546
02:08:51,433 --> 02:08:53,310
<i>It was so beautiful.</i>

1547
02:08:58,023 --> 02:09:01,109
I wish I could've been there with you.

1548
02:09:04,196 --> 02:09:05,614
You were.

1549
02:09:16,333 --> 02:09:17,793
I love you.

1550
02:09:22,172 --> 02:09:25,509
<i>You died on a Saturday morning.</i>

1551
02:09:27,219 --> 02:09:30,973
And I had you placed
here under our tree.

1552
02:09:35,852 --> 02:09:40,691
And I had that house of your father's
bulldozed to the ground.

1553
02:09:44,820 --> 02:09:46,488
<i>Mama</i>

1554
02:09:47,572 --> 02:09:52,577
always said that dying was a part of life.

1555
02:09:55,998 --> 02:09:58,333
I sure wish it wasn't.

1556
02:10:01,003 --> 02:10:04,756
Little Forrest is doing just fine.

1557
02:10:06,091 --> 02:10:07,175
But...

1558
02:10:07,426 --> 02:10:10,095
<i>About to start school again soon,</i>

1559
02:10:11,930 --> 02:10:15,726
and I make his breakfast, lunch
and dinner every day.

1560
02:10:17,894 --> 02:10:23,900
I make sure he combs his hair
and brushes his teeth every day.

1561
02:10:27,029 --> 02:10:29,614
Teaching him how to play Ping-Pong.

1562
02:10:30,907 --> 02:10:31,950
Okay.

1563
02:10:32,200 --> 02:10:33,368
<i>He's really good.</i>

1564
02:10:33,452 --> 02:10:35,579
Forrest, you go.

1565
02:10:39,791 --> 02:10:41,376
<i>We fish a lot.</i>

1566
02:10:44,921 --> 02:10:48,383
(SOBBING) And every night, we read
a book. He's so smart, Jenny.

1567
02:10:51,636 --> 02:10:53,889
You'd be so proud of him.

1568
02:10:55,599 --> 02:10:57,059
I am.

1569
02:10:58,101 --> 02:11:01,313
He wrote you a letter.

1570
02:11:02,898 --> 02:11:04,941
And he says I can't read it.

1571
02:11:05,067 --> 02:11:08,612
I'm not supposed to,
so I'll just leave it here for you.

1572
02:11:24,669 --> 02:11:26,004
Jenny,

1573
02:11:31,802 --> 02:11:35,013
I don't know if Mama was right,

1574
02:11:36,348 --> 02:11:37,849
or if it's Lieutenant Dan.

1575
02:11:37,974 --> 02:11:40,560
I don't know

1576
02:11:40,644 --> 02:11:45,148
if we each have a destiny,

1577
02:11:47,192 --> 02:11:52,322
or if we're all just floating around
accidental-like on a breeze.

1578
02:11:56,827 --> 02:11:58,662
But I think

1579
02:12:00,539 --> 02:12:02,332
maybe it's both.

1580
02:12:06,670 --> 02:12:09,548
Maybe both is happening
at the same time.

1581
02:12:15,679 --> 02:12:17,681
But I miss you, Jenny.

1582
02:12:24,062 --> 02:12:28,483
If there's anything you need,
I won't be far away.

1583
02:13:03,768 --> 02:13:06,730
Here's your bus. Okay.

1584
02:13:08,398 --> 02:13:11,735
Hey. I know this.

1585
02:13:11,860 --> 02:13:14,738
I'm gonna show that
for show-and-tell because

1586
02:13:14,863 --> 02:13:17,532
Grandma used to read it to you.

1587
02:13:17,616 --> 02:13:19,743
My favourite book.

1588
02:13:23,079 --> 02:13:24,581
Here we are.

1589
02:13:24,748 --> 02:13:26,208
Okay.

1590
02:13:27,918 --> 02:13:29,419
Here you go.

1591
02:13:34,299 --> 02:13:36,801
Hey, Forrest, don't...

1592
02:13:40,263 --> 02:13:43,975
- I wanted to tell you, I love you.
- I love you, too, Daddy.

1593
02:13:45,977 --> 02:13:48,772
I'll be right here when you get back.

1594
02:13:53,318 --> 02:13:56,571
You understand this is
the bus to school, now, don't you?

1595
02:13:56,655 --> 02:14:00,200
Of course, and you are Dorothy Harris,
and I'm Forrest Gump.

